============= CLI >>--full<< ====================
usage: ncrystal_minimc [-h] [--full-help] [--tally TALLIES] [--plot]
                       [--geomcfg STR] [--srccfg STR] [--enginecfg STR]
                       [--dump] [--output OUTPUTFILE] [--force]
                       [--input INPUTFILE] [--ref REFFILE]
                       [--doc {geom,src,engine,scenario}] [--decode]
                       [CFGSTR] [SCENARIO]

Run a simulation with NCrystal's builtin MiniMC framework, in order to
investigate effects of geometry and multiple scattering with a particular
NCrystal material and neutron source.

When using this command-line interface, neutron quantities are always tallied in
histograms as the neutrons exit the geometry. By default these results are
simply shown as interactive plots, but options below allow for more advanced
usage such as printing or persistification into files.

For more info in general about the MiniMC or the various configuration strings,
visit: https://github.com/mctools/ncrystal/wiki/minimc

Alternatively, access documentation via the --doc option, or simply input the
string "help" into any option taking a string. For instance, both --doc=src and
--srccfg=help will result in the detailed documentation for source configuration
being shown.

Here are a few examples of usage based on an approach with SCENARIO strings:

1. Pencil beam of neutrons impinging centrally on a diameter=1mfp (mean
   free path between scatterings) sphere of aluminium. Beam energy is
   chosen to be hopefully interesting for the material, based on Bragg
   threshold and temperature:
  $> ncrystal_minimc Al_sg225.ncmat

2. Pencil beam of 2Aa neutrons impinging centrally on a diameter=2mm
   sphere of 300K aluminium:
  $> ncrystal_minimc "Al_sg225.ncmat;temp=300K" "2Aa pencil on 2mm sphere"

3. A zero-divergence beam of 10meV neutrons uniformly illuminating a
   diameter=2mm sphere of 80K beryllium:
  $> ncrystal_minimc "Be_sg194.ncmat;temp=80K" "10meV on 2mm sphere"

4. 1.8Aa neutrons impinging at right incidence on an infinite slab of
   thickness 10cm filled with humid air:
  $> ncrystal_minimc gasmix::air/0.9relhumidity "1.8Aa on 10cm slab"

5. 100000 neutrons at a wavelength which is 99% of the Bragg threshold
   of PG, uniformly illuminating a PG filled sphere whose diameter is 2
   times the mean free path length between scatterings:
  $> ncrystal_minimc C_sg194_pyrolytic_graphite.ncmat "0.99BT on 2mfp 1e5 times"

The --input and --output options allow persistification of results to JSON
format.

positional arguments:
  CFGSTR                NCrystal cfg-string defining sample material.
  SCENARIO              String defining the simulation geometry and neutron source
                        in terms of a simple scenario. For more detailed control,
                        use the --geomcfg and --srccfg flags instead.

options:
  -h, --help            show this help message and exit
  --full-help           Provide more complete usage instructions.
  --tally, -t TALLIES   Comma separated list of tally quantities (select from: de,
                        e, l, mu, nscat, nscat_uw, q, theta, w). Use --tally=help
                        for more information, and the --enginecfg option for more
                        detailed control of e.g. histogram binnings.
  --plot, -p            Launch interactive matplotlib plots of results (default if
                        no other action specified).

advanced options:
  --geomcfg, -g STR     String defining simulation geometry (use --geomcfg=help
                        for more info).
  --srccfg, -s STR      String defining options for the neutron source (use
                        --srccfg=help for more info).
  --enginecfg, -e STR   String defining options for the simulation engine (use
                        --enginecfg=help for more info).
  --dump, -d            Provide summary of results to stdout.
  --output, -o OUTPUTFILE
                        Name of file in which to store results. Must end with
                        .json.gz or .json. As a special case it can be "stdout" if
                        no other output is requested.
  --force, -f           Use with --output to allow overwriting an existing output
                        file.
  --input, -i INPUTFILE
                        Input file name. Used to load previous results (from
                        --output) instead of running new simulations. In this
                        case, no SCENARIO, --geomcfg, --srccfg, or --enginecfg
                        should be specified.
  --ref, -r REFFILE     Reference file name. Used with --plot to overlay previous
                        reference results.
  --doc {geom,src,engine,scenario}
                        Show documentation for the configuration strings available
                        for geometry, source, engine, or scenarios. Alternatively,
                        the same documentation is generated if any of the cfg-
                        strings are equal to the string "help".
  --decode              Show the final cfgstr, geomcfg, srccfg, and enginecfg.

